  "text": "where r ij is the distance between events i and j and w ij is the edge correction [CITATION_1] . We compute the K(.) function for the overall TB population and separately for resident and non-resident population. If the estimated K-function  K r ( ) is significantly higher than πr 2 at distance r then the data demonstrates aggregation or clustering indicative of transmission among infected individuals or of shared environmental factors. On the other hand, a value of  K r ( ) significantly lower than πr 2 indicates 'repulsion' between the two sets. All K(.) curves were estimated under the assumption of inhomogeneous intensity function and compared against an inhomogeneous Poisson process. We used the function, Kinhom(.), of the spatstat package 19 in software R 22 .",
